issue.title: [BUG] Interdimensional Edges out of a portal are not saved

labels.name: incomplete
labels.description: Not every aspect is covered. More information needed.

issue.body: I have a huge canvas I'm using as like a calendar. After installing this plugin, I separated off half the canvas into a sub-canvas, which I then re-added back to the original via a portal. I was able to make an edge from one node into a node inside the portal, and it seems to stick. But when I make an edge from a node inside the portal to a node outside it, whenever the canvas refreshes (and thus the portal takes forever to re-layout; btw, updating the inner canvas doesn't re-layout the outer one), those edges vanish. I looked in at the json and I couldn't find any edges pointing out from the portal. If I make an edge into the portal, the edge appears in the "interdimensionalEdges" map in the json. But if I then take that edge and flip it, the edge outright vanishes from the json file. After flipping, I was expecting there to be an interdimensional edge that was just... ```json { "id":"f9cb4d862581c160", "styleAttributes":{}, "toFloating":false, "fromFloating":false, "fromNode":"f5b0b506defd5c0e-c35c3d593c8940da", "fromSide":"top", "toNode":"a5201c984eb2bd0b", "toSide":"left" } ``` This bug makes it impossible to have a unidirection arrow out of a portal. Using version 5.3.2 on Windows

pull_request.title: Fix data filtering and display logic in parts detail page
pull_request.body:
# Fix data filtering and display logic in parts detail page ## Summary This PR fixes a critical data filtering issue in the parts detail page where all parts were being displayed instead of only the parts related to the selected row from the main table. The root cause was a complex `findOrder()` function that relied on localStorage matching logic, which wasn't working correctly with the actual data structure. **Key Changes:** - **Replaced complex `findOrder()` logic** with direct array access using `rowIndex` from URL parameter `i` - **Removed unused code**: `findOrder()` function, `selected` state, and related matching logic - **Updated data access pattern**: `details` now uses `raw[rowIndex]` instead of `findOrder(raw, selected)` - **Fixed edit/delete functions** to work with the new rowIndex-based approach - **Improved type safety** and error handling throughout the component This ensures that: - Main table correctly displays 5 separate rows (instead of 1 combined row) - Parts detail page shows only the 1-2 part sets belonging to the selected row - Edit and delete functionality works correctly with the properly filtered data ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human - [ ] **Verify main table displays 5 separate rows** - Load the 20250701.png data and confirm the main table shows 5 distinct orders, not a single combined row - [ ] **Test parts detail navigation for multi-part rows** - Navigate to row 4 and row 5 (which have 2 parts each) and verify only those specific parts are shown, not all parts from all rows - [ ] **Test edit functionality end-to-end** - In parts detail page, edit a part's quantity/price, save changes, and verify the 売上金額 recalculates correctly and persists when navigating back to main table - [ ] **Test delete functionality with multi-part sets** - Delete one part from a 2-part row and verify only that specific part is removed, the other part remains, and totals update correctly - [ ] **Test error handling** - Try accessing invalid row indices (e.g., `/detail?i=999`) and verify graceful error handling **Recommended Test Plan:** 1. Upload the 20250701.png file and verify main table shows exactly 5 rows 2. Click "部品詳細" on row 1 → should show 1 part (129670-49290、コックCMP) 3. Click "部品詳細" on row 4 → should show 2 parts totaling ¥3,990 4. Click "部品詳細" on row 5 → should show 2 parts totaling ¥544,800 5. Edit quantities in parts detail and verify calculations update correctly 6. Delete parts and verify only selected parts are removed --- ### Diagram ```mermaid %%{ init : { "theme" : "default" }}%% graph TD MainTable["Main Table
(SevenFieldsTable.tsx)"]:::context DetailPage["Parts Detail Page
(src/app/detail/page.tsx)"]:::major-edit LocalStorage["localStorage
(uploaded-json)"]:::context URLParam["URL Parameter 'i'
(rowIndex)"]:::minor-edit MainTable -->|"Navigate with ?i=rowIndex"| DetailPage DetailPage -->|"Read JSON data"| LocalStorage URLParam -->|"Direct array access: raw[i]"| DetailPage subgraph "Old Logic (Removed)" OldFindOrder["findOrder() function"]:::major-edit OldSelected["selected state from localStorage"]:::major-edit end subgraph "New Logic" NewRowIndex["rowIndex from URL param"]:::major-edit NewDirectAccess["raw[rowIndex] direct access"]:::major-edit end subgraph Legend L1["Major Edit"]:::major-edit L2["Minor Edit"]:::minor-edit L3["Context/No Edit"]:::context end classDef major-edit fill:#90EE90,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px classDef minor-edit fill:#87CEEB,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px classDef context fill:#FFFFFF,stroke:#333,stroke-width:1px ``` ### Notes **Architecture Change:** This PR represents a significant architectural shift from a complex, error-prone data retrieval pattern to a simple, predictable one. The old `findOrder()` approach tried to match orders based on multiple fields (受注番号, 納入先番号, 出荷日) stored in localStorage, but this was fragile and didn't work correctly with the actual data structure. **Data Structure Context:** The system processes PNG images via Dify AI to extract purchase order data. Each order can have 1-2 part sets, where each part has 5 fields: 部品番号, 部品名, 数量, 売上単価, 売上金額. **Session Info:** Requested by 衣斐司郎 (@shiro-mail) - [Devin Session](https://app.devin.ai/sessions/9ccd62075abe477aac596b39dd55ee59) **Risk Assessment:** Medium-High - This is a core data filtering refactor that touches the main user workflow. While the new approach is simpler and more reliable, thorough testing is essential to ensure no regressions in edit/delete functionality or edge cases.

issue.body:
## Which issue does this PR close?

This PR closes issues:
- #46 
- #47

## Rationale for this change

- #46 goal planner resets to older/preset values on clearing up and pressing enter which might lead the user to input wrong values if they haven't checked properly or constantly run into issues with old values popping up.
- #47 changed 'rerun' function with suitable version of streamlit.

## What changes are included in this PR?

- #47 changed `st.experimental_rerun()` to `st.rerun()`
- #46 added proper placeholders and logic.

## Are these changes tested?
Yes.
## Are there any user-facing changes?

No.

issue.title: [Balance - Enemy threat level] Enemies can spawn in greater numbers to make the balance more engaging

type.name: Feature
type.description: A request, idea, or new functionality

issue.body:
**Environment**: Windows build

**Description**: Currently, there are way too few enemy spawns. The player can safely do each room just by proceeding very slowly. The stealth part of the gameplay really isn't necessary at all. Rooms are often mostly empty, and the player is forced to just walk around.

The game could really spice up the enemy threat by quite a bit, to allow the stealth gameplay to shine as well. For example, as the day count gets higher, there can be rooms that are almost filled with enemies everywhere, and the player is encouraged to just sneak past everything or take an alternative route.

However, this will likely be quite time consuming to adjust the balance to be just right.

issue.title: Phase 3: Real-time Collaboration Features
issue.body:
## Overview
Build a comprehensive real-time collaboration system enabling multiple agents and users to work together seamlessly with live updates, conflict resolution, and intelligent handoffs.

## Technical Requirements

### Core Features
- **Live Cursor Sharing**
  - Real-time cursor position tracking
  - User/agent avatar display
  - Smooth cursor animations
  - Multi-file cursor tracking
  - Viewport synchronization option

- **Conflict Resolution System**
  - Operational Transformation (OT) algorithm
  - Three-way merge for conflicts
  - Automatic conflict detection
  - Visual conflict markers
  - Rollback capabilities

- **Agent Handoff Protocols**
  - Context preservation during handoffs
  - Task state transfer
  - Session recording and replay
  - Handoff request/approval flow
  - Emergency takeover mechanisms

- **Pair Programming Mode**
  - Driver/navigator roles
  - Role switching protocols
  - Shared terminal sessions
  - Voice chat integration
  - Screen annotation tools

### Technical Architecture
```typescript
interface CollaborationSession {
  id: string;
  participants: Participant[];
  activeFile: string;
  cursors: CursorPosition[];
  changes: OperationalTransform[];
  conflictResolver: ConflictResolver;
  handoffProtocol: HandoffManager;
}

interface Participant {
  id: string;
  type: 'user' | 'agent';
  role: 'driver' | 'navigator' | 'observer';
  cursor: CursorPosition;
  viewport: ViewportState;
  permissions: Permission[];
}
```

### Implementation Details
1. **WebSocket Infrastructure**
   - Socket.IO for real-time communication
   - Redis pub/sub for scaling
   - Message queuing for reliability
   - Presence detection system
   - Connection state management

2. **Conflict Resolution**
   - CRDT implementation for text
   - Vector clocks for ordering
   - Automatic merge strategies
   - Manual resolution UI
   - Conflict history tracking

3. **Performance Requirements**
   - <50ms latency for cursor updates
   - <100ms for text synchronization
   - Support 50+ concurrent users
   - 99.99% message delivery rate
   - Automatic reconnection

## UI/UX Requirements
- Smooth cursor animations (60fps)
- Non-intrusive conflict indicators
- Clear role indicators
- Intuitive handoff interface
- Accessibility compliance (WCAG 2.1)

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Real-time cursor tracking with <50ms latency
- [ ] Conflict resolution with zero data loss
- [ ] Handoff completion in <2 seconds
- [ ] Support for 10+ simultaneous collaborators
- [ ] Pair programming with voice/video
- [ ] Session recording and playback
- [ ] Full test coverage (>85%)
- [ ] Load testing with 100+ users
- [ ] Documentation and tutorials

## Dependencies
- Socket.IO for WebSocket management
- Redis for pub/sub and caching
- WebRTC for voice/video
- Y.js or similar for CRDT
- FFmpeg for session recording

## Priority
**P1** - Essential for team collaboration

## Estimated Effort
4 weeks (3 developers)

## Technical Lead
@Alex_Thompson - UI implementation critical

## Related Issues
- Depends on WebSocket infrastructure
- Integrates with authentication
- Connects to notification system

commits.message:
Adds toggle for advanced filtering to improve mod panel performance (#1219)

Introduces an option to enable or disable advanced filtering features,
allowing users to control whether additional mod data (e.g. folder size,
author, modified date) is shown in the mods panel. Disabling advanced
filtering hides related UI elements and skips heavy calculations,
addressing performance concerns for large mod sets.

(I made this an option because I don’t like it scanning the whole disk
and it makes the two mod panels different in size)

https://github.com/RimSort/RimSort/pull/1190#issuecomment-3194035286

Refactor styles across multiple pages to utilize a modern color palette and typography system

- Updated color variables to use OKLCH for better color accuracy.
- Standardized typography using CSS variables for font sizes, weights, and line heights.
- Refactored background, border, and shadow styles for consistency across components.
- Enhanced hover effects and transitions for buttons and cards.
- Improved accessibility by ensuring color contrast and semantic color usage.

Add SQS-based delayed processing for alarm events

Introduces SQS integration for asynchronous, delayed processing of Unifi Protect alarm events to improve video download reliability. Updates Lambda handler to support both API Gateway and SQS events, adds queueing logic, and extends CloudFormation with SQS resources and configurable processing delay. Documentation and OpenAPI spec are updated to reflect the new architecture and flow.
